What's the #1 thing to know when renting on Turo?  

THIS ONE THING is why less than 1% of travelers use car-sharing services (like the one you're on right now).

The appeal of car-sharing cannot be denied, which offer an endless variety of vehicle choices, more flexible pickup/delivery times and locations, and the convenience of having your own dedicated on-call customer service agent (the host).  

Yes, some people also come to find an amazing deal, even while rental car shortages continue to plague the industry and prices surge.  

But, why hasn't the car-sharing marketplace exploded and disrupted the entire 9-5, choose your used-and-abused economy/mid-size/not-real-luxury car,  waste-1-hour-shuttling-to-rental-facility, waste 20 more minutes with begrudged clerk who couldn't WFH, worse-than-a-DMV x2, retail impound?

Afterall, car-sharing has been around for nearly as long as other ultra-successful peer-to-peer services such as Uber and AirBNB which have significantly displaced their respective industries.  

So what gives?  Keep reading.

Let's say you're curious and have decided to give car-sharing a try.  You go through all the steps of setting up your account, perform countless vehicle searches, get the pickup location and times exactly as you like, and find that special vehicle which you're sure to enjoy.  You hit the "book trip" button and voila!--Your perfect trip is scheduled.  

It feels great to have a major part of your travel plans all set and put behind.  You're really looking forward to taking that beauty for a spin.  

But what if, time comes and you're within days or even hours of the start of your trip, only to receive this dreaded notification: "YOUR HOST [name of host] HAS CANCELLED THE TRIP."  F-bleep!

You see, a host is in ultimate control of their own vehicle.  And any host can cancel an upcoming trip for their vehicle for any reason, and without notice.  

You (the guest) have no recourse other than to go and find another vehicle, often within hours or minutes from the time you need it.  You may lose that convenient location you've planned on, and waste hours of additional time.  You may have to settle for a second-rate vehicle, which is certainly not the car you were so looking forward to driving.  You may pay more.  

This happens more often than you might think!

Of course, there are many things that can make or break your rental experience, but last-minute host cancellations is one of the main reason why many renters leave car-sharing and never come back. 

Antiquated bricks-and-mortar car rental companies have many drawbacks, but they still provide assurance that bookings are substantially safe from cancellation.

So, the *most* important thing to know when booking your car on Turo is knowing your host won't leave you hanging within hours, or even minutes, of your arrival.

Turo does not publish hosts' commitment rates (aka, follow-through).  And "Response Rate" does not equal Commitment Rate.  Always check the host's reviews for cancellation notices.  You may be surprised to find that many "All-star Hosts" have repeated cancellations history.

I'm very proud to offer my lineup of new and beautifully maintained Tesla vehicles.  I'm also proud to offer delivery to either of the major Chicagoland airports, Union Station or a custom address of your choosing.

Thank you for considering me and my vehicle for your upcoming trip, and I look forward to working with you!

Dale Z.
